04418nam a22007575i 9780271084305DE-B159720230328044521.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230328t20192019pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710843057 a10.1515/97802710843052doi  a(DE-B1597)584585  a(OCoLC)1262307681  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aART0090002bisacsh04a701/.82231 aRose, Sam, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRefiguring Modernism. Art and Form :bFrom Roger Fry to Global Modernism /cSam Rose. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b27 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRefiguring Modernism ;v2800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart One. Art Writing -- t1. Form and Modernist Aesthetics On or About 1910 -- t2. The Science of Art Criticism After the 1910s -- tPart Two Art and Life -- t3. Mass Civilization and Minority Visual Culture -- t4. Design Theory and Marxist Art Writing: For and Against Mass Culture -- t5. Modernism and Form in Africa, Britain, and South Asia— -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis important new study reevaluates British art writing and the rise of formalism in the visual arts from 1900 to 1939. Taking Roger Fry as his starting point, Sam Rose rethinks how ideas about form influenced modernist culture and the movement’s significance to art history today.In the context of modernism, formalist critics are often thought to be interested in art rather than life, a stance exemplified in their support for abstract works that exclude the world outside. But through careful attention to early twentieth-century connoisseurship, aesthetics, art education, design, and art in colonial Nigeria and India, Rose builds an expanded account of form based on its engagement with the social world. Art and Form thus opens discussions on a range of urgent topics in art writing, from its history and the constructions of high and low culture to the idea of global modernism. Rose demonstrates the true breadth of formalism and shows how it lends a new richness to thought about art and visual culture in the early to mid-twentieth century.Accessibly written and analytically sophisticated, Art and Form opens exciting new paths of inquiry into the meaning and lasting importance of formalism and its ties to modernism. It will be invaluable for scholars and enthusiasts of art history and visual culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aArt criticism. 0aArtxPhilosophy. 0aFormalism (Art). 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh  aFormalism.  aRoger Fry.  aaesthetics.  aart criticism.  aart history.  aglobal modernism.  amodernism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311074520740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271084305?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271084305423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271084305/original  a978-3-11-074520-7  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK